Citation.sTitle: Thermodynamics of proton dissociation from aqueous bicarbonate: apparent molar volumes and apparent molar heat capacities of potassium carbonate and potassium bicarbonate at T=(278.15 to 393.15) K and at the pressure 0.35 MPa
Citation.sAbstract: We have determined the apparent molar volumes V and apparent molar heat capacities Cp, of aqueous potassium carbonate and potassium bicarbonate solutions in the ranges (0.014m/(mol ? kg-1)0.51) and (278.15T/K393.15) at the pressure p=0.35 MPa. Corrections for speciation due to hydrolysis and disproportionation in solution were applied using Young's rule, and semi-empirical equations representing (V,m,T) and (Cp,,m,T) for the species {2K+, CO32-(aq)} and {K+, HCO3-(aq)} were fitted to the experimental results. We have used these equations to estimate the change in volume rVm, change in heat capacity rCp,m, enthalpy change rHm, entropy change rSm, and equilibrium molality quotient pQ for the second proton dissociation reaction from aqueous carbonic acid.
